{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_bajoran_ver01/data/sn85042243/0019991859A/1924052701/0967.xml":{"full_text":"[=\"ssh THE BISMARCK TRIBUNE I\nESTABLISHED 1873\n35 KNOWN DEAD IN\nCOOPERATION\nTO AID STATE\nIS PROPOSED\nF. P. Mann of Devils Lake Ad\ndresses Retail Merchants\nAssociation Here\nCONVENTION OPENS\nBusy Three Days, with Busi\nness Program, Is Provid\ned For Visitors\nA program of increased coopera\ntion between retail business men and\nthe farmer and united elFort in fur\nthering the interests of the state,\nwas urged upon retail merchants\nhere at the opening session of the\nNorth Dakota Detail Merchants As\nsociation today, by Fred P. Mann of\nDevils Lake, president of the otgan\nization.\n\u201cBetter business methods, both by\nthe merchants and farmers of North\nDakota, is the only way to bring\nprosperity to North Dakota\nsaid Mr. Mann, delivering the presi\ndent\u2019s message. \u201cWe have made\nsome little progress the past few\nyears but not anywhere near as much\nas we should have made. I think the\nlack of cooperation of all the busi-\nness interests of the state together\nwith the farmer is responsible for\nf most of our trouble. The lack of\ngood sound leadership, not only in\nbusiness, but in politics is the grave\nmenace to the return of prosperity\nin our state at the present time.\n\u201cWhat we need more than any-\nthing else is big honest, hard work\ning sound thinking business men and\nfarmers at the head of our organiza\ntions, as well as the state, county and\ncity government. Until such time as\nthe representative business men, and\nfarmers of the state of North Dakota,\nwill give their time and money to\nput on a real constructive business\nprogram in North Dakota, we will not\nprosper.\u201d\nUrges Organization\nMr. Mann urged that retail mer\nchants organize in their own towns\nto work in conjunction with farming\ninterests, declaring the diversified\nfanning movement can be put over\nfaster if the business people of the\ntowns'get into the harness. He in\ndorsed the Greater North Dakota As\nsociation.\nAn optimistic outlook on business\nwas taken l>y Mi. Mann, who said\ncrop prospects arc favorable over\nthe entire state, presaging better\nactivity in business in the summer\nand fall.\nThe attendance at the opening ses\nsion was expected to he augmented\nwith the attendance of inuny more\nmerchants for the second and third\nday se&sions. A large number of\nrepresentatives of various jobbing\nand manufacturing firms are here\njfcith exhibits.\nThe opening session was in Pat\nterson Hall, the headquarters being\nat the McKenzie hotel. Mayor A. P.\nLenhart welcomed the visitors in be\nhalf of the city. Preliminaries took\nup most of the morning session, in-\ncluding reports by Treasurer F. W.\ni Peglow and Secretary W. A. Don\ny nelly.\nRoy P. Logan of Bismarck conduct\ned a question box this afternoon, and\ntalks were made by R. E. Wenzel on\n\u201cRetail Laws\u201d and by B. E. Hitch\ncock, deputy collector of internal\nrevenue, on \u201cBusiness Records.\u201d\nSpeakers Tomorrow\nSpeakers tomorrow will include E.\nF. Flynn, assistant to the Vice-Pstsi\ndent of the Great Northern Railroad;\nGovernor R. A. Nestos; F. D. Newell\nof Minneapolis; B. V. Moore, deputy\ngovernor, Federal Reserve Bank,\nMinneapolis; John DeWild, adver\ntising manager, Ely Walker Dry\nGoods Company, St. Louis, Missouri.\nA banquet will be held Wednesday\nnight at 7 p. m. at the McKenzie ho\ntel, and local merchants are urged to\njoin in thfs affair. Many Bismarck\ntraveling men remained in the city\nfor the convention, expecting many\nmere-.ants in their territory to come\nhere for the convention.\nConvention committees include\ngeneral convention chairman and\nsecretary, Fred J. Grady, Bismarck;\n4ntertainment committee, W. H.\nifebb and Roy P. Logan, Bismaiek;\nchairman traveling men\u2019s entertain\nment committee, C. M. Henry Hollst;\nhostess to the visiting ladies, Miss\nInez Jones.\nVisiting ladies are expected to be\nguests on a picnic tonight, leaving\nthe Business and Professional Wo\nmen's clubrooms at 6 p. ni., with\nMiss Jones in charge.\nBarker Bakery, it was announced,\n\u2022would keep open house after the Au\nditorium meeting Wednesday night,\nshowing how bread is nfode by ma\nchinery, and how candy is made.\nVENUE CHANGE\nIS GRANTED\nFargo, N. D., May 27.\u2014Chunge of\nvenue from Ransom to LaMoure\ncounty was granted in the ease of\nRay Craig, former president of the\nRansom County Farmers bank, ac\ncording to W. H. Barnett, attorney\nfor the defendant. The case is ex\npected to be heard during the June\nterm of district court in LaMoure\ncounty.\nMr. Craig, formerly state manager\nof the Nonpartisan league, is held on\na charge of embezzlement in connec\ntion with the failure of the bank of\njvhich he was president,\nWORLD FLIERS DISABLED AT CORFU\n\u00abfe;~ Ttlr|B|i i 1 'f SWPr\nAlaj.ir Stuart MaiLcnin (rig'. h\\.<ler of the British round-the\nworld flight, shown stranded in lie harbor of Corfu where eilgine\ntrouble forced a landing. Blank ts and food were brought to them by\nColonel and Stephen K. Live i St. Louis. Mo., American Near East\nRelief workers, who are shown visiting the stranded plane.\nEBERT SEEKING\nFORMATION OF\nNEW CABINET\nChancellor Marx May Remain\nin it on a New Align\nment of Forces\nEFFECT ON DAWES PLAN\nBerlin, May 27. Germany today\nwas in the throes of another gov\nernment crisis through the resigna\ntion of the Marx-Stresemann cabi\nnet and President Ebert was ex\npected- to consult the various party\nleaders as soon as the Reichstag\nreconvened with vjvw to solution\nof tlio difficulty.\nChancellor Marx is continuing to\nconduct business at the President s\nrequest and it is expected the whole\naffair may result simply in a re\nalignment of the ministry with\nMarx still in power.\nThe goverrtment\u2019s resignation re\nsulted in a long-drawn out attempt\nto construct a straight bourgcoi.se\ncoalition which could work with the\nReichstag as composed on the basis\nof the recent election.\nBRITISH VIEW\nLondon, May 27 The German cab\ninet shuffle has placed the Da,wes\nreparation settlement plan in a po\nsition'of uncertainty so fur as Ger\nmany's acceptance is concerned, hut\nBritish officials who arc keeping in\nclose touch with events in Berlin,\nhold to the opinion, formed some\ntime ago,, that no German govern\nment can conceivably be so stupid\nus to reject the experts\u2019 proposals.\nIt is believed here that the contin\nuity is hound to include acceptance\nof the Dawes committee recommen\ndations.\n\u201c\u2019WHITE WAY\"\nIS DISCUSSED\nCommissioners Seek Solution\nto Troublesome Problem\nCity commissioners* last night dis\ncussed the \u201cWhite Way\u201d system\nThe question of what to do with\nthe Bismarck* system has been a\npuzzler for sometime. Most cities\nhave discarded the five-cluster light\nsystem as used here, for rather plain\npoles with one top light, both us be\ning more artistic ami more economi\ncal.\nThe present system here is expen\nsive to maintain. Small boys and\nwind combine to destroy globes fre\nquently, the wiring is poor on many\nof the circuits and the commission\ners do not like to spend much money\non a system now held obsolete.\nIt was dt-cided that the commis\nsion would avail itself of the free\nservice of the General Electric Com\npany to have an illuminating en\ngineer come to the city and go o\\er\nthe system.\nNEW CHURCHES\nARE ADMITTED\nFargo, hL D., May 27.\u2014Admission\nof seven new congregations to the\nNorth Dakota district, Norwegian\nLutheran church of America, and dis\ncussion of budget, reduction, were\namong the items of business taken up\nby the annual convention of the dis\ntrict in its sessions here today.\nThe seven ahurches admitted were\nthe Vang Lutheran church, Dunn\nCenter; Rose Valley church, Des\nLacs; Leonard Lutheran church;\nFirst Englishf Lutheran church of\nCathay; Vaage church at Brocket;\nGrand Valley Sanish, and\nthe Lutheran church at Kintyre.\nPark Workers\nOn Special Train\nA special train will be run through\nFaigo on the morning of June 11\nover the Northern Pacific, carrying\nsome 800 people employed during the\nsummer season at Yellowstone Na\ntional Park.\nEvery spring a train is made up at\neither Chicago or St. Paul especial\nly for these employes. The group is\ncomposed largely of School teachers\nand students who work at the park\nduring the summer months for theii\nvacation. This year the train runs\nfrom St. Paul to Gardiner.\nSUSPECT HELD\nIN PROBE OF\nFRANKS CASE\nWhs Driving Automobile of\nKind Near Private School\nBoy Attended\nChicago, May 27. \u2014Arrest of a man\nknown as George Johnson, \u2014the\nname signed to the ransom lettc* re\nceived By Jacob Franks demanding\nSIO,OOO for the return of his son,\nRobert, 12, driving a gray automo\nbile\u2014was the latest development in\nthe investigation today of the kid\nnaping and death of the boy.\nThe prisoner was driving the make\nof automobile seen near the private\nschool when the Franks boy disap\npeared.\nThe prisoner, known as Johnson,\nalthough his name is Adolph Pu\npritz, said he was not surprised by\nhis urrest.\n\u201cI expected it, everybody with a\ngray car is being taken in,\u201d the swe\npe.ct said.\nHe saiil he knew nothing of the\nFranks case, that his parents liveo in\nAkron, Ohio, and that he was about\nto leave on a trip to lowa. Oir the\nafternoon of the kidnaping, last Wed\nnesday, he said he was motoring\nwith a woman whose name he\ndid not know.\nGIRL FOUND\nChicago, May 27.-'\u2014Gertrude Bark\ner, 10-year-old academy student,\nthought to have been the victim of\nkidnapers since her disappearance\nlast Wednesday, waiP found last\nnight keeping house in a stable\nkeeper\u2019s apartment. She had taken\nup duties of sweeping and cooking\nin preference to school work.\nJuvenile Band Ticket\nDrive Starts\nWednesday\nCommittees will go out to\nmorrow in a rapid fire drive\nto\nfor the Juvenile Band Benefit\nconcert at the Auditorium,\nFriday evening, May 30.\nIt is hoped through this\nconcert to secure funds\nenough to carry the work\nthrough until fall and to aid\nin financing a few outdoor\nconcerts during this summer.\nA number of women have\nconsented to aid in this drive\nfor a most worthy educational\nfeature of community effort.\nThere will be a concert in\nthe afternoon following the\nexercises of the American\nLegion. This concert will be\ngiven at the High School Au\nditorium for the \u201ckiddies.\u201d\nBand members are selling\nchildren\u2019s tickets at fifteen\ncents each. Adults can attend\nthis concert if they desire.\nHelp boost the \u201cKiddies\nBand.\u201d\nBISMARCK, NORTH DAKOTA, TUESDAY, MAY 27, 1924\nSHORT BALLOT\nBEFORE VOTERS\nIN N. D. JUNE 25\nOnly 53 Names on Ballot For\nJunp 25 Primary Nomina\ntions in the State\nSOME BLANK PLACES\nDemocrats Have no Candi\ndates For 2 Congressional\nand One State Place\nflic June 25 primary ballot in\nNorth Dakota will be the shortest\nin years.\nThere are but 53 candidates on th\u00ab*\nstate ballot, exclusive of district\njudges, there are no initiated or re\nferred measures or constitutional\nnmendenients for the first time in\nJ ears at a state election, and in\ntwo districts there is no contest on\nfor places on the district bench.\nGenerally it will be a straight\nline-up in the Republican primary\nbetween candidates indorsed by the\nheal Republican state convention at\nJt' mestown and the Nonpartisan\nLeague state convention in Bismarck.\nHowever, I. J. Moe of Valley City\nmakes a third Republican candidate\nfor Governor, and O. A. Hall, Fargo,\nfor whom petitions were filed late\nyesterday makes a third man in the\nrace for Secretary of State.\nExcepting in the second district\nthere are hut two candidates for\nthe Republican nomination for Con\ngressman. In this district, E. A.\nWilliams and Thomas Hall of Bis\nmarck and John Sherman of Steele\nare competing.\nThe Democratic ticket has some\nblank spaces. Petitions were not\nfiled to place candidates in the race\nfor Congressman either in the Sec\nond or Third districts, and no Demo\ncratic candidate appeared for Com\nmissioner of Agriculture and Labor.\nMartin C. Frcerljs of Jamestown is\nthe sole candidate whose name will\ngo in the \u201cNonpartisan League\nParty\u201d column, he being a candidate\nfor Congress in the Second district.\nJudgeship Race\nFour district judges will have no\nopposition. In the Third district,\ntwo to be elected, the only candi\ndates are George M. McKenna of\nNapoleon and (\u2019has. E. Wolfe of\nWahpeton, incumbants; and in the\nfourth district, two to he elected,\nthe only candidates are J. A. Coffey\nof Jamestown ami Fred Jansonius of\nBismarck/ incumbents.\nFor the supreme court, two to be\nnominated and one elected, there\nare six candidates as follows: John\nBurke, Fargo; Joseph Coghlan, Bis\nmarck, Charles J. Fisk, Minot, Frank\nB. Fectham, Grand Forks; G. Crim\nson, Langdon; F. O. Hellstrom,\nBismarck.\nList of Candidates\nThe complete list of candidates\nfollows:\nREPUBLICAN\nRepresentatives in Congress\nFirst District \u2014ll. 11. Anker, Grand\nForks; O. B. Burtness, Grand Forks.\nSecond, District' \u2014Thomas Hall,\nBismarck; John Sherman, Steele; E-\nA. Williams, Bismarck.\nThird District \u2014M. O. Hall, Mo\nhall; James 11. Sinclair, Kenmarc.\nGovernor \u2014I. J. Moe, Valley City;\nRagnvald A. Nestos, Minot; Arthur\nG Sorlie, Grand Forks.\nLieutenant Governor-\u2014Walter Mail\ndock, Plaza; Frank E. Ployhar, Val\nley City.\nSecretary of State\u2014Robert B.vrnc\nArnegard; O. A. Hall, Fargo; D. E\nShipley, Dickinson.\nState Auditor\u2014David C. Poindex\nter, Jumestown; John Steen, Rugby.\nState Treasurer \u2014C. A. Fisher\nValley City; John O. Lyngstud\nBismarck.\nAttorney General \u2014George F. Sha\nfer, Watford City; T. H. H. Thore\nsen, Dunn Center.\nCommissioner of Insurance- Si\nmon J. Nagel, Glen Ullin; S. A.\nOlsness, Sheyenne.\nCommissioner of Agriculture and\nLabor \u2014William J. C'hurfch, York;\nJoseph A. Kitchen, Seritinel Butte.\nCommissioners of Railroads\u2014(Six\nto be nominated) \u2014Fay Harding,\nLinton; M. P. Johnson, Tolley; M.\n11. Lynch, Lidgerwood; C. W. Mc-\nDonnell, Kensal; Frank Milhollan.\nBismarck; L. L. Russell, New Rock\nford.\nDEMOCRATIC\nRepresentatives in. Congress:\nFirst District\u2014Walter Wolford\nNcche.\nGovernor \u2014Halvor L. Halvorsori,\nMinot; L. S. Platou, Fargo.\nLieutenant Governor--James H.\nMcCoy, Wahpcton.\nSecretary of state \u2014Lillian Gu\nbelmaSi, Valley City.\nState Auditor \u2014George Lconhardy,\nWilliston.\nState Treasurer \u2014J. V. Birder,\nPark River.\nAttorney General Tobias 1)\nCasey, Dickinson.\nCommissioner of Insurance\u2014W.\nS. Hooper, Fargo.\nCommissioners of Railronds \u2014L. M.\nByrne, Napoleon; Edward Hadley.\nEllendale; Edwar/d Kibler, Cavalier.\nNONPARTISAN PARTY\nRepresentative in Congress:\nSecond District\u2014Martin C. Frccrks\nJamestown.\nNONPARTISAN\n(No party affiliation)\nJudge of the Supreme Court\n(Two to be nominated) \u2014John Burke,\nFargo; Joseph Coghlan, Bismarck;\nCharles J. Fisk,, Minot; Frank B.\nFeetham,* Grand Forks; G. Grimson,\nLangdon. F. O. Hellstrom, Bismarck.\n(Continued on page 3)\nSOUTHERN STORMS\nFORD\u2019S SHOALS\nBID DEFEATED\nIN COMMITTEE\nSenate Body Votes to Report\nOut Goverhmcnt Opera\ntion Measure\n\\QTE IS EXPECTED\nBoth Proposals Likely to be\nActed Upon in Senate\nThis Session\nWashington, May 27. The Norris\nbill for goverment operation of\nMuscle Shoals was reported favor\nably today by the Senate .agricul\nture committee by a vote of 11 to 4.\nA motiop to report the Ford bid\nwas defeated, 11 to 5. Favorable\nartioii was taken on the Norris bill\nwhen it was offered as a substitute\nfor the Ford proposal.\nSenator Ladd, Republican, North\nDakota, and Johnson, Farmer-Labor,\nMinnesota, voted for the Norris bill.\nSenator Ladd also voted for the Ford\noffer, Senator Johnson voting\nagainst it.\nOn the Norris bill Senators Car\naway, Arkansas, ajid Ralston, lndi-\nLoth voted present.\nSenator Harrison, Democrat, Mis\nsissippi, champion of the Ford pro\nposal. declared after the executive\nsession that the committee's action\nmeant that a vote could be taken in\nthe Senate on both the Ford and\nNorris bills.\nFIVE HELD ON\nSUSPICION OF\nBANK ROBBERY\nMinot Police Take Quintet\nWith Car Alleged Stolen\nin South Dakota\nCLOTHING IS STOLEN?\nMinot, N. May 27.\u2014-Five men\nsupccted l>y Minot authorities of be\ning implicated in a recent robbery\nof a hank at Abercrombie, North\nDakota, are held in the city and\ncounty jails today, following their\narrest at Kenmare late yesterday, on\ncharges of drunkeness.\nThe men\u2019s names according to\nauthorities, are: Wlhitey\" Cline\nalias Header, alius Eau Claire\n\u201cWhitey\u201d; \u201cDevils Lake Red\u201d alias\nLinden; Dan Morris; W. E. Arnold\nalias \u201cSharkey\u201d and Herman Rich\nman \u201calias Rich.\u201d\nA large touring automobile, alleg\ned by the authorities to have been\nin possession of the quintet, has\nbeen identified as having been stolen\nfrom George Slater at Aberdeen, S.\nD. on May 13, officials state. None\nof the men is willing to lay claim\nto owneishij) or previous possession\nof the car.\nA telephone message received by\nSheriff Spicher of Minot this after\nnoon, from the sheriff of Richland\ncounty, at VVahpeton, states that he\nhas warrants charging bank robbery\nagainst the quintet and that he wilt\narrive in Minot tomorrow to take\nthem into custody. It is possible\nthe Wahpeton sheriff said, that the\nemployc'of the bank who was in the\ninstitution when it was robbed, and\nwho was bound and gagged, will ac\ncompany him to Minot and endeavor\nto identify them as being men who\nentered the bank.\nSheriff Spicher said this afternoon\nthat he would not be willing to say\nhe would turn the entire five over\nto Whhpeton authorities, inasmuch\nas a sheriff from Rugby also is in\nthe city and has identinfied various\narticles of clothing worn by each as\nbeing that stolen on May 20 at Silva,\nN. D.\nTHREATENS\nMANDAN MEN\nNegro Is Held on Charges in\nMandan Today\nMandaii, N. D., May 2*7. \u2014Dan Ed\nwards, colored, odd jobs man, is in\nthe Morton county jail awaiting\nhearing tomorrow on charges of\ngrand larceny and faces further\ntrial on charges of threatening to\nkill Otto Bauer, general manager of\nthe Bingcnheimer Mercantile .Com\npany chain of lumber yards and E.\nR. Lantcrman.\nLantcrman, president of the Man\ndun' cemetery association, refused\nEdwards the right to work in the\nMandan cemetery because of the al\nleged intemperate habits. Yesterday\nafternoon Edwards, it is alleged,\nstole a shot gun and started out\nthreatening to kill Bauer and Lan\nterman. Edwards at the present\ntime is under indictment by fed\neral grand jury on a charge of sell\ning liquor to Indians.\nDR. C.O. ROBINSON CRUSHED BY\nSTREET CAR IN MINNEAPOLIS;\nIS TAKEN TO HOSPITAL THERE\nChild Prodigy\nI.ureiie Kohner of Minneapolis, at\n3 years old, is writing shorthand.\nAnd lie knows his geography well\nenough to take a map ami pick out\nthe principal rivers and countries in\nthe western hemisphere, lie can\nskate, and swim, too. But right now\nbis greatest ambition in life is to\nl\u00bbc\u00bb another Babe Ruth or Ty Cobb.\nTAX MEASURE\nTO PAY BONUS\nLEADERS AVER\nT reasury Reports Indicate\nSufficiency of Receipts, Ac\ncording to Chairman Smoot\nBILL TO COOLIDGK\nWashintgon, May 27. Republican\norganization leaders were hopeful\ntoday that President Coolidgo will\nmake an early and favorable deci\nsion on the tax reduction hill sent\nto him yesterday by \u2022'engross.\nIn addition to receiving the over\nwhelming vote of Congress a total\nof only lfi votes being cast against\nit \u2014the measure was declared by\ntreasury department officials analy\nzing it to be an improvement over\nthe present law. I\u2019resident Coolidgc\nlias let it lie known that he will\nconsider the hill on its merits* in\nrelation to the present law and will\nact on the preponderance of the ad\nvantages or disadvantages he finds\nafter such a comparison.\nThe measure represents little of\nthe original tax reduction plan ad\nvanced by Secretary Mellon and ask\ned of Congress by I lie I\u2019resident.\nThe principal treasury objections to\nthe bill, however, are understood to\ncenter on opening tax returns to\npartial publicity and increasing the\nestate taxes.\nOn the basis of treasury esti\nmates, both Chairman Smoot of the\nsenate finance committee and\nChairman Green of the house ways\nand means committee said that the\nmeasure, despite its heavy tax re\nreduction proposal, will raise suf\nficient revenue to meet all govern\nment expenses next year and pay for\nthe bonus as well.\nSORLIE OUT\nBY JUNE 15\nGrand Forks, N. D., May 27.\u2014A. G.\nfcorlie, league candidate for gover\nnor, who is in a Grand Forks hospi\ntal, following his removal there fiom\na Bismarck hospital, said in a state\nment issued from the Grand Forks\nhospital, addressed to the league ex\necutive committee:\n\u201cAm writing this to show my ap\npreciation of your efforts in behalf\nof the principles so dear to our\nheart#. I am confident that your\nwork is being well done, from the re\nports that I receive of the growth of\nsentiment in favor of our cause.\n\u201cAm very sorry that the doctor's\norders are that I rest for two or\nthree more wefcks which will prevent\nme from being with you to do my\nshare. I am feeling very well now\nand shall be with you by June 15, to\nassist in the fight which must bo\nwon.\nBISMARCK TO PAY TRIBUTE TO\nWAR DEAD ON MEMORIAL DAY\nBismarck's tribute to the soldiers\nof past wars will be made Memorial\nDay in the afternoon, with a parade\nand public exercises in the City Au\nditorium.\nThe parade, in which all ex-service\nmen are urged to be in uniform, will\nbe at 2 p. m., followed J>y the Audi\ntorium exercises at 2:30 p. nl.\nScott Cameron will deliver the\neulogy to the dead of past wars, and\nan interesting program will include\nInjuries May Not Be as Seri\nous as at First Indicated,\nAccording to Information\nReceived from Dr. V. .1.\nLa Rose\nDr. Robinson of Bismarck\nwas injured last night in an auto\nl mobile accident in Minneapolis,\n\"here be was visiting while on his\nwa,\\ ln>me from lowa with his fam-\nThe seriousness of the accident\nwas not determined today. Dr. V.\nJ. Lultose, who is in Minneapolis at\ntending u Rotary club meeting, w\nreached from here and he went to\nthe hospital to see Dr. Robinson.\nlie reported in a telegram that Dr.\nRobinson did not appear to be as\nseriously injured as at first feared,\nbut that X-rays taken would not be\ndeveloped until late in the day, when\nthe exact nature of tne injuries\nwere expected to be disclosed.\nA news dispatch from Minneapolis\nlast night said that Dr. Robinson\nwas working on his automobile,\nwhich was parked near Thirty\neighth street when a street car back\ned around a corner and pinned him\nagainst his machine. This report\nsaid Dr. Robinson\u2019s back was brok\nen. but it was felt here that this\nreport was exaggerted.\nDr. Robinson jam! .family were\nstopping at the home of a brother\nin-law in Minneapolis, -and were ex\nported baek here by June 1.\nHe is in the Fail-view hospital,\nMinneapolis.\nIS SOME BETTER\nMinneapolis, May 27.\u2014(8y the A.\nI'.) \u2014Dr. O. Robinson of Bismarck,\nN. D., injured in an automobile ac\ncident here yesterday, was reported\nin a \u201cbetter condition\u201d yesterday at\nFairview hospital. Dr. Robinson was\nhit by a street car while working on\nliis parked automobile.\nJAPAN LIKES\nATTITUDE OF\nTHE PRESIDENT\nMessage May Not, However,\nHave Much Effect on the\nMasses of I'eople\nTokio, May 27\u2014(By the A. I*.)\n1 he statement of*President Coolidge,\naccompanying his signature of the\nAmerican immigration bill, with its\nclause excluding Japanese from that\ncountry, was described by a foreign\noffice spokesman today as \u201ca source\nof great comfort to Japan.\u201d\nThis spokesman said it is believed\nthe statement would he effective in\nlessening to some degree agitation\nagainst America here.\nFrom the same source it was learn\ned here that officials here under\nstood Mr. Coolidge\u2019s position and\nappreciated the stand he took. Oth\ners said they feared the public ef\nfect of the statement would he small\nas the masses of the Japanese, not\ncomprehending the niceties of the\nsituation, would see only the fact\nthat they are excluded from the\nUnited States which they consider a\nnational insult.\nCO. EXHIBITS\nARE PLANNED\nVt Least Six Expected to ijo\nTo County Fairs\nSix county exhibits are expected to\nbe sent from North Dakota to coun\nty fairs in Illinois, lowa, eastern and\nsoutheastern Wisconsin and southern\nMinnesota this summer, according to\nJ. M. Devine, Commissioner of Agri\nculture and Labor. They are: Barnes,\nMorton, Sargent, Steele, Ramsey,\nTowner. Exhibits may also be sent\nout by Hettinger, Ward and Burleigh\neou nties.\nUnder the plan, the county exhibits\nof agricultural products will be hous\ned in tents at county fairs, and North\nDakota\u2019s ability to raise eorn, alfal\nfa, sweet clover and vegetables will\nbe stressed. The six exhibits will\nreach 48 counties, being shown at two\nfairs each week for one month, it is\nexpected.\nrendition of Lincoln\u2019s famous Gettys\nburg speech by George Knowles,\nmusic by a chorus from the Thursday\nMu sic Club and choirs of the city,\nsolo by Henry Halverson and invo\ncation by Rev. Ryerson.\nThe graves of the dead will be de\ncorated in the morning, and flowers\nstrewn on the waters of the Missouri\nin honor of the sailor dead.\nCapt. H. T. Murphy will be in\ncharge of the parade.\nFINAL EDITION\nPRICE FIVE CENTS\nTORNADOES HIT\nTHREE STATES\nCAUSING HAVOC\nFeared That Additional Re\nports Will Greatly In\ncrease the Death Toll\nFAMILIES WIPED OUT\nTen Are Reported Dead iu\nOne Small Community Alone,\nFrom the Storm\nAtlanta, Ga\u201e May 27.\u2014(Rv\nthe A. P.\u2014A series of torna\ndoes sweeping through Mi\nsissippi, Alabama and Louisi\nana last night and*early toda/\ntook a known toll of thirty\nfive lives and caused injury to\nupwards of 70 persons and\nwrought thousands of dollars\ndamage to farms and build\nings, according to advices\nreaching here today from\nvarious sections of those\nstates.\nIn Mississippi there were known\nto be dead and the list of injured\nstood at fifty early today after sev\neral storms had torn through the\nsouthern section of the stute. At\nCollins two young girls are reported\nto have lost their lives, 12 were in\njured, many seriously and virtually\nthe entire business district wiped\naway.\nHits Many Communities\nThe storm also struck Johnson\nstation, Vicksburg and Grenville\nlate yesterday and today another\ntwister swooped down in the vicinity\nof Ray Springs and Collins, causing\nreports of deaths and injury to sev\neral families living in that region.\nOther communities in Mississippi\nat which deaths were reported in\ncluded Swain Plantation, near\nGrenville, where three negroes were\nkilled and a dozen others injured;\nUnion, eight injured; Waynesboro,\nseveral negroes killed, and Summitt,\nwhich is T?aid to 'have suffered\nheavy property loss.\nHeaviest in Alabama\nEarly reports from Alabama placed\nthat stale as the next heaviest suf\nferer from the storm. Ten were re\nported dead at tin* Owens Mminp\nCommunity near Empire City, ir\nWalker county, and the list of in\njured there stood around 15. Thre<\nfamilies were reported annihilated\nin the little mining community. Sev\neral members of the family of Billy\nRobbins were killed and Mrs. John\nHayes and a young woman natnec\nAbbott lost their lives there, Johr\nHayes being perhaps fatally injured.\nReports reaching here from Athens\nplaced the number of dead at seven\nin the Ellumont neighborhood, the\nfamily of Will Collins having been\nkilled and a baby two years old\nblown completely away.\nIn Louisiana Vestcr Carr is\nthought to be fatally injured, hav\ning been struck by lightning late\nyesterday during a heavy rainstorm\nthere. Reports continued to come\nin and it is feared the death toll\nand list of injured will reach great\ner proportions when more definite\ninformation is available.\n10 DIED\nEmpire, Alabama, May 27. \u2014Tw.\u00bb\nfamilies wert> practically wiped d.i\nin the Owens mining camp t v o\nmiles from here early today v i\nIn persons were killed and fifteen\ninjured in a storm that struck y hil\nthey slept. The home of Billy\nbins and John llayes were snia\ninto splinters.\nIn the Robbins household eig'-.t\npersons were killed. Mrs. John\nJlaycs and a young woman named\nAl hot met death in the Hayes hor o\nand Hayes was so badly hurt it i\nbelieved lie will die. Several house\nin the vie'nitv of the Robbins an t\nHayes homes were demolished.\nENTIRE FAMILY KILLED\nNashville, Tcnn., May 27. \u2014A spe\ncial to the Banner from Athens,\nAlabama, says a tornado struck\nLimestone county Monday, killing\nseven east of Ellumont. The entire\nfamily of Will Collins were all kill\ned. A two-year-old baby was blown\naway.\nMANY INJURED\nGadscn, Alabama, May 27.\u2014Eight\npersons were injured, a number ser\niously, in a storm that struck the\nWhite Sulphur Springs community\nseven miles from Gadscn early to\nday. Four of the more seriously in\njured were brought to hospitals\nhere.\n17 KNOWN DEAD\nNew Orleans, May 27.\u2014 At least\n17 dead and 50 injured was the toll\nof storms that swept through Mis\nsissippi last night.\nTO NOMINATE\nW. G. McADOO\nChicago, May 27.-p(By the A. P.l\n\u2014James E. Phelan of San Francisco,\nformer United States Senator fron\nCalifornia, has been selected to plac\u2022>\nthe name of William G. McAdoo\nbefore the Democratic national con\nvention in New York, it was leaned\nhere today.","height":"28407","width":"22260"}}
